<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-599-834  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 599 834.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  July 2 1990 v7 n26 p6(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Judge rules in Lotus' favor in copyright suit. (Lotus DevelopmentCorp.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Ferranti, Marc.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Paperback Software International (cases)Lotus Development Corp. (cases)Stephenson Software Ltd. (cases).andO;Ticker:    LOTS.andO;Topic:     United States. District Court. MassachusettsCourt CasesCopyrightSoftware Publishers.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Marc FerrantiandM;In a decision that sets the stage for a landmark appeals case, the U.S.andO;District Court in Boston ruled last week that the developers of VP-Plannerinfringed Lotus Development Corp.'s copyright of 1-2-3 by imitating thespreadsheet's user interface.andM;Focusing on the interface's menu command structure in a 115-page decision,Judge Robert Keeton wrote that the copying by Paperback SoftwareInternational and Stephenson Software Ltd., development partners ofVP-Planner, was &quot;overwhelming and pervasive.&quot;andM;Paperback, which plans to appeal, had contended that it was merely trying toconform its spreadsheet to the de facto standard and that VP Planner'sunderlying code differed from 1-2-3's.andM;The ruling affirms the application of copyright law to software designestablished in earlier cases and may affect the outcome of decisions pendingin other cases, legal analysts said.andP;  It also paves the way for the FirstCircuit Court of Appeals to make a ruling that could cap a decade-long trendthat has seen legal protection for computer programs move from object code touser interface.andO;</TEXT></DOC>